2710	\begin{proof}
2711	  \uses{lem:isLocalization_basicOpen_of_qcqs_mathlib, lem:isLocalizedModule_constructor_mathlib,
2712	    lem:isUnit_res_basicOpen_mathlib, lem:compact_open_induction_mathlib,
2713	    lem:isIso_fromTildeΓ_of_presentation_mathlib, lem:isLocalizedModule_tilde_restrict,
2714	    lem:isLimitPullbackCone_mathlib, lem:existsUnique_gluing_mathlib,
2715	    lem:isLocalization_basicOpen_mathlib}
2716	  Write \(N = \Gamma(M, \top)\). We build the witness directly as the three-field predicate
2717	  \(\mathrm{IsLocalizedModule}(\mathrm{powers}\,f)\) (\cref{lem:isLocalizedModule_constructor_mathlib})
2718	  on the restriction \(N \to \Gamma(M, D(f))\), mirroring exactly how the structure-sheaf qcqs lemma
2719	  \cref{lem:isLocalization_basicOpen_of_qcqs_mathlib} assembles \(\mathrm{IsLocalization.Away}\,f\)
2720	  from its three pointwise axioms. No finite equalizer object and no flatness of localization are
2721	  used.
2722	
2723	  \emph{Shared core (step 1 -- the only manual ingredient also present in the equalizer route).}
2724	  From the quasi-coherence datum \(M.\mathrm{QuasicoherentData}\) extract a finite basic-open tilde
2725	  cover: refine the given cover to the basis of basic opens, take a finite subcover by
2726	  quasi-compactness of \(\Spec R\), and transport the local presentation across each affine
2727	  identification \(D(g) \cong \Spec R_g\), using \(\Gamma(\Spec R, D(g)) = R_g\)
2728	  (\cref{lem:isLocalization_basicOpen_mathlib}). On each \(D(g)\) the transported presentation makes
2729	  \(M|_{D(g)} \cong \widetilde{N_g}\) (\cref{lem:isIso_fromTildeΓ_of_presentation_mathlib}), so the
2730	  affine tilde localization (\cref{lem:isLocalizedModule_tilde_restrict}) computes the sections of
2731	  \(M\) on sub-basic-opens of \(D(g)\). Unlike the equalizer route, Route~F needs no explicit
2732	  equalizer/limit object and no proof that the \(g_a\) generate the unit ideal.
2733	
2734	  \emph{map\_units.} The \(R\)-action of \(f^n\) on \(\Gamma(M, D(f))\) factors through
2735	  multiplication by the restriction of \(f\) to \(D(f)\), which is a unit of the structure ring
2736	  \(\Gamma(\mathcal{O}, D(f))\) (\cref{lem:isUnit_res_basicOpen_mathlib}); hence \(f^n\) acts
2737	  invertibly on \(\Gamma(M, D(f))\).
2738	
2739	  \emph{surj.} Every section of \(M\) on \(D(f)\) is \(f^{-n}\) times the restriction of a global
2740	  section, for some \(n\). This is proved by induction over the compact open \(D(f)\)
2741	  (\cref{lem:compact_open_induction_mathlib}): the base case is an affine \(D(g)\), where the claim
2742	  is the affine tilde localization from step~1; the inductive step glues a section already defined
2743	  on an open \(S\) with one on an affine \(D(g)\), agreeing on the overlap, via the sheaf
2744	  Mayer--Vietoris square (\cref{lem:isLimitPullbackCone_mathlib}) and unique gluing
2745	  (\cref{lem:existsUnique_gluing_mathlib}) applied to the concrete sheaf
2746	  \(\mathrm{modulesSpecToSheaf}(M)\).
2747	
2748	  \emph{exists\_of\_eq.} If a global section restricts to \(0\) on \(D(f)\), then \(f^n\) annihilates
2749	  it for some \(n\). The same compact-open induction applies, with the base case again the affine
2750	  tilde localization and the inductive step the uniqueness half of gluing
2751	  (\(\mathrm{eq\_of\_locally\_eq'}\), \cref{lem:existsUnique_gluing_mathlib}).
2752	
2753	  Supplying these three fields constructs \(\mathrm{IsLocalizedModule}(\mathrm{powers}\,f)\) for the
2754	  restriction \(N \to \Gamma(M, D(f))\), as required.
2755	\end{proof}
